{{Infobox language |name=Hill Nubian |altname=Kordofan Nubian |states=[[Sudan]] |region=[[Nuba Hills]] |ethnicity=(see [[Hill Nubian]]) |speakers={{sigfig|63,350|2}} |date=1984–2013 |ref = e18 |familycolor=Nilo-Saharan |fam2=[[Eastern Sudanic languages|Eastern Sudanic]] |fam3=[[Astaboran languages|Astaboran]] |fam4=[[Nubian languages|Nubian]] |lc1=ghl|ld1=Ghulfan |lc2=kdu|ld2=Kadaru |lc3=kko|ld3=Karko |lc4=wll|ld4=Wali |lc5=dil|ld5=Dilling |lc6=drb|ld6=Dair |lc7=elh|ld7=El Hugeirat |glotto=kord1246 |glottorefname=Kordofan Nubian }}The '''Hill Nubian languages''', also called '''Kordofan Nubian''',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=G_RKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA203|title=Dotawo: A Journal of Nubian Studies: Vol. 1: 2014|last=Jakobi|first=Angelika|last2=Ruffini|first2=Giovanni|last3=Oei|first3=Vincent W. J. van Gerven|date=2014-06-03|publisher=punctum books|year=|isbn=9780692229149|location=|pages=203|language=en}}</ref> are a group or [[dialect continuum]] of [[Nubian languages]] spoken by the [[Hill Nubians]] in the northern [[Nuba Mountains]] of [[Sudan]].
== Classification == The Hill Nubian languages are generally classified as being in the Central branch of the Nubian languages, one of three branches of the Nubian languages, the other two being Northern ([[Nile]]), consisting of [[Nobiin language|Nobiin]], and Western ([[Darfur]]), consisting of [[Midob language|Midob]]. They are grouped together with [[Kenzi language|Kenzi]]-[[Dongolawi language|Dongolawi]] (not seen to be closely related to Nobiin, despite their proximity) and [[Birgid language|Birgid]], a language of southwestern Sudan extinct since the 1970s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/subgroups/nubian|title=Nubian|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2017-06-24}}</ref> Nubian lies within the [[Eastern Sudanic]] family, which is part of the [[Nilo-Saharan]] phylum.
== Languages == There are seven Hill Nubian languages, according to ''Ethnologue'' and Glottolog. Some of the languages have dialects. Their internal classification within Hull Nubian is not well established. Glottolog classifies Hill Nubian (Kordofan Nubian) into two branches: Eastern Kordofan Nubian and Western Kordofan Nubian, containing three and four languages respectively.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/kord1246|title=Glottolog 3.0 - Kordofan Nubian|last=|first=|date=|website=glottolog.org|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-06-24}}</ref> ''Ethnologue'', however, only groups Kadaru and Ghulfan together, leaving the rest unclassified within Hill Nubian, as follows:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/subgroups/hill|title=Hill|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2017-06-24}}</ref> * Kadaru-Ghulfan ** [[Ghulfan language|Ghulfan]] (also Gulfan, Uncu, Uncunwee, Wunci, Wuncimbe) – 33,000 speakers ** [[Kadaru language|Kadaru]] (also Kadaro, Kadero, Kaderu, Kodhin, Kodhinniai, Kodoro, Tamya) – 25,000 speakers * [[Dair language|Dair]] (also Dabab, Daier, Thaminyi) – 1,000 speakers * [[Dilling language|Dilling]] (also Delen, Warkimbe, Warki) – 11,000 speakers * [[El Hugeirat language|El Hugeirat]] (also El Hagarat) – 50 speakers * [[Karko language (Sudan)|Karko]] (also Garko, Kaak, Karme, Kithonirishe, Kakenbi) – 7,000 speakers * [[Wali language (Sudan)|Wali]] (also Walari, Walarishe, Wele) – 9,000 speakers Additionally, one extinct language known only from a word list of 36 words, [[Haraza language|Haraza]], is unclassified within Hill Nubian.
