{{Infobox person | name = Jan Lofting | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Jan Loftingh | birth_date = {{birth year|1659}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{d-da|15 June 1742|1659}} | death_place = | nationality = [[Netherlands|Dutch]] | other_names = | occupation = | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''John Lofting''' (1659 – 15 June 1742, [[London]]), originally '''Jan Loftingh''', was an engineer and entrepreneur from the Netherlands. His parents were Herman and Johanna. He moved to London, England, before 1686.<ref name=trentmannn/> He patented two inventions: the "sucking worm engine" (a [[fire engine]])<ref>{{cite book |title=Jan Van Der Heyden: 1637-1712 |last=Sutton |first=Peter C. |page=234 |year=2006 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=9780300119701 }}</ref> and a horse-powered [[thimble]] knurling machine.<ref name=trentmannn/> His mill was set up in [[Islington]], where Lofting Road is named after him.<ref>{{cite book |title=The streets of London: a dictionary of the names and their origins |last=Fairfield |first=Sheila |page=196 |year=1983 |publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] |isbn=9780333286494 }}</ref> However, in or about 1700, he moved his main operation to [[Great Marlow]] in Buckinghamshire to take advantage of the [[River Thames]]' ability to turn a [[water wheel]] which improved productivity, enabling the production of over 2 million thimbles per year.<ref name=trentmannn>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Handbook of the History of Consumption |last=Trentmann |first=Frank |page=77 |year=2012 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780191624353 }}</ref>
