{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Marine Day |type = national |image = |imagesize = 255px |caption = |official_name = |nickname = |duration = 1 day |scheduling = nth weekday of the month |frequency = annual |observedby = Japan |longtype = National |significance = Honors the blessings of the oceans and economic prosperity of maritime Japan |week_ordinal = third |weekday = Monday |month = July |celebrations = |observances = |relatedto = }} {{Nihongo|'''Marine Day'''|海の日|Umi no Hi}}, also known as "Ocean Day" or "Sea Day", is a [[Public holidays in Japan|Japanese national holiday]] celebrated on the third Monday in July. The purpose of the holiday is to give thanks to the [[ocean]]'s bounty and to consider the importance of the ocean to Japan as an island nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www8.cao.go.jp/chosei/shukujitsu/gaiyou.html|script-title=ja:国民の祝日について|publisher=[[Cabinet Office (Japan)|Cabinet Office]], Government of Japan|language=Japanese|accessdate=July 17, 2012}}</ref>
Many people take advantage of the holiday and summer weather to take a beach trip. Other ocean-related festivities are observed as well.<ref name="UH"/> The date roughly coincides with the end of [[East Asian rainy season|tsuyu]] ([[East Asian rainy season|rainy season]]) in much of the Japan mainland.{{cn|date=July 2017}}
==History== The day was known as {{nihongo|Marine Memorial Day|海の記念日|umi no kinen bi}} until 1996. [[Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications|Communications Minister]] Shozo Murata designated the day in 1941 to commemorate the [[Meiji Emperor]] and his 1876 voyage in the [[Meiji Maru]], an [[iron steamship]] constructed in Scotland in 1874.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaiyodai.ac.jp/english-c/en-facilities/12374.html|title=The Meiji-maru|publisher=[[Tokyo University of Marine Science and Technology]]|accessdate=July 17, 2012}}</ref> The voyage included a trip around the [[Tōhoku region]], embarking on a lighthouse boat in [[Aomori, Aomori|Aomori]], and a brief stop in [[Hakodate]] before returning to [[Yokohama]] on July 20 of that year.<ref name="Iida2002">{{cite book|last=Iida|first=Masao|title=橋から見た隅田川の歴史 (History of the Sumida River as seen from a bridge)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kYP45frzjFAC&pg=PA52|accessdate=July 17, 2012|date=June 2002|publisher=文芸社|language=Japanese|isbn=9784835538945|page=52}}</ref> However, it was not designated a national holiday until 1995, when it became the first holiday in the summer months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jetprogramme.org/e/culture/holidays/09.html|title=Marine Day (Third Monday of July)|work=[[JET Programme]]|publisher=[[Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology]]|accessdate=July 17, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120530173605/http://www.jetprogramme.org/e/culture/holidays/09.html|archivedate=May 30, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
First observed on July 20, 1996, the [[Happy Monday System]] legislation moved the date to the third Monday of July beginning in 2003.<ref name="UH">{{cite web|url=http://www.crosscurrents.hawaii.edu/content.aspx?lang=eng&site=japan&theme=cal&subtheme=PUBLICHOL&unit=JCAL006|title=Marine Day (Third Monday in July)|work=Cross Currents|publisher=[[University of Hawaii]]|accessdate=July 17, 2012}}</ref>
